I get the appeal of that idea, but it overstates what’s actually possible.

You can influence how people feel and what they pay attention to.
You can’t make someone “adopt your reality” just by staring or by covertly steering them.

What is real (and useful) is attentional guidance and presence:

* Eye contact & stillness can signal confidence and focus.
* Clear framing (“Here’s the problem, here’s the goal”) organizes attention.
* Tone and pacing help people follow your line of thought.
* Shared evidence lets others choose to update their views.

That’s influence through clarity, trust, and context, not hidden control.

A clean, effective approach

* State the frame openly: “I’m looking at it this way—does this fit what you’re seeing?”
* Offer reasons and examples: give people something to evaluate.
* Invite response: “Where does this break?”
* Adjust based on feedback.

Why this works better

* It respects agency, so people don’t push back.
* It scales—people will carry the idea forward because they chose it.
* It holds up under scrutiny—no need to hide the method.

Quick guardrail

If you find yourself relying on “they shouldn’t realize what I’m doing,” that’s a sign to switch back to transparent alignment.

Compression

Don’t try to replace someone’s reality.
Make yours clear, testable, and worth choosing.